-- Chesapeake Energy Bonds Decline to Lowest in More Than a Year
-- B y   S r i d h a r   N a t a r a j a n
-- 2012-01-20T18:17:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-20/chesapeake-energy-bonds-decline-to-lowest-in-more-than-a-year.html
Bonds from  Chesapeake Energy Corp. (CHK) ,
the most active U.S. oil and natural-gas driller, dropped to the
lowest level in more than a year.  The company’s $1.3 billion of 6.625 percent notes maturing
in August 2020 fell as much as 4 cents to 98 cents on the
dollar, according to Trace, the bond-price reporting system of
the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority. The securities
reached the lowest level since December 2010, snapping two days
of gains. The bonds traded at 99.25 cents to yield 6.74 percent
as of 12:44 p.m. in  New York , Trace data show.  The securities have declined 8.5 cents this month, the
biggest monthly fall since they were issued in August 2010,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. Chesapeake is rated BB+
by  Standard & Poor’s  and a step lower at Ba2 by Moody’s
Investors Service.  To contact the reporters on this story:
